# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# REPO-ROOT .env  →  read by the Node scrape sidecar (api/bridges/scrape-server.ts)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Copy to `.env` (gitignored). The Python service has its OWN file: api/.env
# (see api/.env.example). Both must exist on the droplet — the deploy never touches
# them (gitignored), so set them by hand once.

# ScraperAPI — powers the proxy fallback that reads pages a direct fetch can't.
# CRITICAL ON PROD: the droplet is a datacenter IP, so pinkblue, amazon, buzzdent,
# medidentalpro … all block the direct fetch and ONLY work through this proxy.
# Local dev mostly works without it (residential IP), so this is the #1 thing that
# makes prod behave differently if missing/expired.
SCRAPER_API_KEY=

# OPTIONAL speed optimization. pinkblue blocks datacenter IPs, but smartFetch now
# AUTO-falls back to ScraperAPI when the direct fetch is blocked/errors — so prod
# reads pinkblue correctly even WITHOUT this flag. Setting it to 1 on prod just skips
# the doomed direct attempt first (saves ~8s per pinkblue fetch). Leave UNSET locally
# (residential IP reaches pinkblue directly — no proxy, no credits).
# PROXY_PINKBLUE=1
